00:05:47.850 --> 00:05:51.000
So here is omega ba.

00:05:51.000 --> 00:05:54.430
That's one of the frequencies
in the black-body of radiation.

00:05:54.430 --> 00:05:59.300
But there are many,
many more nearby.

00:05:59.300 --> 00:06:02.610
And they are incoherent.

00:06:02.610 --> 00:06:05.220
That is, in the
black-body of radiation,

00:06:05.220 --> 00:06:09.300
each amplitude for a
different frequency

00:06:09.300 --> 00:06:11.340
is independent of
the other ones.

00:06:11.340 --> 00:06:13.170
They're, like, random.

00:06:13.170 --> 00:06:16.350
So here is our sum, therefore.

00:06:16.350 --> 00:06:22.650
We must, we know, that when we
have several inputs, not just

00:06:22.650 --> 00:06:25.720
one electric field but
many electric fields,

00:06:25.720 --> 00:06:29.970
we will have to add the
transition probability caused

00:06:29.970 --> 00:06:32.940
by the different
electric fields.

00:06:32.940 --> 00:06:36.420
And in this case,
we will have to sum

00:06:36.420 --> 00:06:38.550
the effects of
the electric field

00:06:38.550 --> 00:06:43.800
squares of the many components
of the black-body of radiation

00:06:43.800 --> 00:06:47.520
that lie near this omega ba.

00:06:47.520 --> 00:06:51.420
That is the one that would
trigger a transition.

00:06:51.420 --> 00:06:55.670
So this is how we're
going to obtain

00:06:55.670 --> 00:07:00.610
something that will look like a
Fermi golden rule as well here.

00:07:00.610 --> 00:07:02.480
There is a transition.

00:07:02.480 --> 00:07:06.590
The transition is
between discrete states.

00:07:06.590 --> 00:07:09.550
But the trigger
for the transition

00:07:09.550 --> 00:07:13.150
is a superposition of
electromagnetic waves

00:07:13.150 --> 00:07:16.030
that we have to integrate over.

00:07:16.030 --> 00:07:25.370
So one can say that the
electric field, electric field

00:07:25.370 --> 00:07:50.180
